= David Cyrluk
== Former Mentee at GE R&D · Later PhD Researcher at Stanford/SRI

I heard from Dran about Deepak's passing. I just want to take a few moments to convey my condolences and deep appreciation for the role Deepak had in my life.

He was my first mentor at GE's R&D center at my first job out of college. In addition to his intelligence and hard work, he brought a commitment to me and my life that I felt and that made a real difference for me. He was also very blunt. I remember once, after sharing a very initial draft of a paper with him, his reaction was simply, "This sucks." Not exactly what you want to hear from your supervisor, but appreciated in the end. He was straight with everyone he dealt with, and I knew that bluntness came from a place of caring and wanting me to do as well as I am capable of.

Another incident reflecting his straightforward style was when he noticed I wasn't dating and didn't have any girlfriends. At the time, I was extremely shy and nervous around women. In his blunt style, he just came up to me and asked me straight up about his not seeing me date. You can imagine how self-conscious and maybe embarrassed I might have felt, having a deficit just stated bluntly to me like that, but then again, it was an indication of Deepak's deep caring about me, not just as a computer scientist and colleague, but as a complete person and friend.

One last memory: I was at Stanford and SRI working on my PhD thesis research, working on what would be a paper covering the last bit of research I needed to complete my PhD work, and while it was going to be a solo paper on my part, I remember talking back and forth with Deepak to help me make it as good as possible. He never stopped caring about me and being there for me.

I lost touch, as I did with many old friends, after my mental illness, but I was able to reconnect a little while ago, where I was able to share some of my writing and new plans. I am doing well now, and I have no doubt how happy Deepak would be to know that.

In my Jewish tradition, we say, "may their memory be a blessing" for those we have lost. Deepak was a real blessing in my life, especially in my formative years right out of school. As I remember all the ways he was there for me and what a special and unique person he was, his memory will be a continued blessing to me for the rest of my life.

With deep sorrow for your loss.

