= Anand Tandon
== Friend and IIT Kanpur Alumnus · New Delhi

I am deeply saddened Deepak is not with us anymore. For unknown reason, good people leave us earlier than most.

In IIT Kanpur, Deepak and I did not know each other. We were not friends, or even acquaintances. He was in electrical engineering, and I in mechanical, so our paths seldom crossed. Yet, less than a decade ago, and without meeting personally, we became friends, thanks to a twist of fate.

Deepak was brutally honest, and passionate, about his politico-economic thoughts about India, and shared them openly in our IITK alumni email network. Hundreds of blind sycophants of the ruling party pounced on him around 2017 or so, for no decent reason, merely to rudely negate his views. I could not remain a silent bystander, so castigated all such in very strong and undiplomatic language. That one act somehow endeared me to him. Such was his graciousness, that from strangers one day we became — and remained — friends for years.

You could say we met for the first time when you and Deepak invited us to your home for dinner in 2021. You were gracious hosts, and my wife Sujata and I were overwhelmed by your hospitality. Deepak and I last exchanged messages on August 30, 2024, when he visited Delhi. I tried to advise him about his dental work, but he had to return to the US immediately, and we could not even meet.

Roli, please let me know if you or Ila come to Delhi or Lucknow again. Please count me as one of Deepak's friends in Delhi, and one eager to keep alive our friendship even after he has gone. Stay strong, because it allows us to relive the wonderful times with Deepak, and remember too how much he enriched our lives. Thank you, Deepak, for who you were, and how beautifully you touched all our lives.

